activities.message:
@7h0r4pp4n It's not the request to delete the user that's associating the old authentication token with the new session, it's the initial login request for the second account.

If you create the first user and then delete them (storing the delete request in Burp), close your browser and re-open (or delete cookies and refresh the login page), this attack _shouldn't_ succeed. What I think is happening -- and I'm still trying to verify this -- is that when you register your second account you're doing so still using the old session ID associated with the first account. When you validate your email address the second time and are logged in a new session ID is created, but the old authentication token has already been declared valid for the new user. Burp can save all of these values but only GitLab can associate the auth token with a new session.

Another way to test this would be to run two web browsers, both using Burp as a proxy, and see if it still works. Use each browser for only one user. I've done this and it doesn't appear to work.
